'''Takeoshi Yama Tarine''' (建忍山垂根) is a figure mentioned in ancient Japanese texts such as the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''. He is regarded as the progenitor of the {{ill|Hozumi clan|ja|穂積氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Genealogy ==
The genealogy of Takeoshi Yama Tarine is not detailed in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}'' or the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''. However, he is identified as the father of {{ill|Otodokoro no Iratsume|ja|弟財郎女|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, who became an empress of {{ill|Emperor Seimu|ja|成務天皇|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

He is also recognized as the father of the sisters {{ill|Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|ja|大橘比売命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Princess Ototachibana|ja|弟橘媛|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, both of whom are associated with the legendary prince {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|倭建命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} as recorded in the ''Kojiki'', ''Nihon Shoki'', and ''{{ill|Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki|ja|常陸国風土記|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}''.

== Historical Mentions ==
In the ''Kojiki'' section about Emperor Seimu, Takeoshi Yama Tarine is introduced as the father of {{ill|Otodokoro no Iratsume|ja|弟財郎女|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a consort of the emperor. Additionally, he is described in the ''Kojiki'', ''Nihon Shoki'', and ''Hitachi Fudoki'' as the father of {{ill|Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|ja|大橘比売命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Princess Ototachibana|ja|弟橘媛|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. These sisters are featured prominently in the mythology surrounding Yamato Takeru.

Takeoshi Yama Tarine is enshrined as a deity at {{ill|Hozumi Shrine|ja|穂積神社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Oshiyama Shrine|ja|忍山神社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

