He is also recognized as the father of the sisters {{ill|Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|ja|大橘比売命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Princess Ototachibana|ja|弟橘媛|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Princess Ototachibana|qq=}}, both of whom are associated with the legendary prince {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|倭建命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|qq=}} as recorded in the ''Kojiki'', ''Nihon Shoki'', and ''{{ill|Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki|ja|常陸国風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki|qq=}}''.
== Historical Mentions == In the ''Kojiki'' section about Emperor Seimu, Takeoshi Yama Tarine is introduced as the father of {{ill|Otodokoro no Iratsume|ja|弟財郎女|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otodokoro no Iratsume|qq=}}, a consort of the emperor. Additionally, he is described in the ''Kojiki'', ''Nihon Shoki'', and ''Hitachi Fudoki'' as the father of {{ill|Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|ja|大橘比売命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otachibana-hime no Mikoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Tachibanahime-no-Mikoto|lt=Princess Ototachibana|ja|弟橘媛|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Princess Ototachibana|qq=}}. These sisters are featured prominently in the mythology surrounding Yamato Takeru.
